description:
## Problem
`backend/middleware/requestBodySecurity.mjs:250-257` contains a silent try/catch that swallows every non-AppError exception thrown during JsonScanner execution:

```js
export function verifyJsonBody(req, _res, buffer) {
  const contentType = req.headers['content-type'] || '';
  if (!contentType.includes('application/json') || buffer.length === 0) {
    return;
  }

  try {
    const raw = buffer.toString('utf8');
    new JsonScanner(raw).scan();
  } catch (error) {
    if (error instanceof AppError) {
      throw error;
    }
    // ⚠ every other error class silently swallowed
  }
}
```

This is the SAME silent-swallow primitive the 21R-SEC-3 (Equoria-expn) commit message names as the threat model: "without a depth cap, a deeply nested payload overflows the call stack — combined with any silent catch upstream, that bypasses BOTH defenses." The depth-cap throw propagates because it is an AppError, but ANY other exception class (a future RangeError that escapes the depth check at the boundary, a TypeError from a future code change, regex catastrophic-backtrack on `skipWhitespace`'s `/\s/`, etc.) is silently dropped. The verify hook returns silently, express.json then parses the body normally, and the protection is bypassed.

This violates `.claude/rules/EDGE_CASE_FIX_DISCIPLINE.md` Rule 3:
> No silent catches. Ever. In security-critical code (anything in `backend/middleware/*Security*`...): ❌ `try { ... } catch (e) { /* swallow */ }` ❌ `try { ... } catch (e) { if (e instanceof X) throw e; }` (silent for non-X)

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Failing test added FIRST in `backend/__tests__/integration/security/`. Test injects a non-AppError exception into the scanner path (e.g., monkey-patch `JsonScanner.prototype.scan` to throw a `RangeError`, OR send a payload that legitimately produces a non-AppError throw via the existing scanner) and asserts the request returns 400.
- [ ] Implement fail-closed re-throw: `} catch (error) { if (error instanceof AppError) throw error; logger.error('[RequestBodySecurity] Unexpected scanner error', { error: error.message, stack: error.stack }); throw new AppError('Invalid request body', 400); }` (or equivalent — the requirement is non-AppError errors MUST result in HTTP 400, not silent pass-through).
- [ ] AC test passes after the fix.
- [ ] No new bypass headers, no test.skip, no try/catch swallowing reintroduced.
- [ ] The error class actually thrown for unexpected errors is logged (so we don't lose forensic data).

## Verification commands
```
# Failing test FIRST:
cd backend
node --experimental-vm-modules node_modules/jest/bin/jest.js \
  --config=jest.config.security.mjs \
  __tests__/integration/security/<new-test-name>.test.mjs --no-coverage

# Then implement fix in middleware/requestBodySecurity.mjs.

# Then re-run — must pass:
node --experimental-vm-modules node_modules/jest/bin/jest.js \
  --config=jest.config.security.mjs \
  __tests__/integration/security/<new-test-name>.test.mjs --no-coverage

# Regression check:
npm run test:security
```

## Background
Found in code review of commit `f06c9ed6` (21R-SEC-3, Equoria-expn). The depth-cap implementation is correct as far as it goes, but the silent catch upstream defeats the fail-closed contract. Fix is independent of the depth cap; both defenses must succeed.

Hard rules from `.claude/rules/EDGE_CASE_FIX_DISCIPLINE.md`:
- Rule 1: failing test FIRST
- Rule 3: no silent catches in security middleware
- Rule 8: no new bypasses
